This paper investigates censorship from a linguistic perspective, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the categories of computational linguistics (cs.CL), social and information networks (cs.SI), and information retrieval (cs.IR). Additionally, the study involves building a classifier, which could also place it in the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR) due to the potential privacy implications of censorship. Finally, the focus on readability could also suggest a connection to computer systems and human-centered computing (cs.CY).
